name: Inflection
desc:
Use this simple Kanban template to keep the engineering team on the same page and moving through work fluidly. 

1. Break down the roadmap by adding tasks as cards to the **Backlog** list. 

2. Move the cards one-by-one through **Design** as they becomes more fleshed out. *Pro tip:* You can enable Power-ups for your favorite design tools like [Figma](https://trello.com/power-ups/59b2e7611e6ece0b35eac16a/figma) or [Invision](https://trello.com/power-ups/596f2cb2d279152540b2bb31), in order to easily link and view designs without switching context.

3. When a card is fully specced out and designs are attached, move it to **To Do** for engineers to pick up. 

4. Engineers move cards to **Doing** and assign themselves to the cards, so the whole team stays informed of who is working on what.

5. Cards then move through **Code Review** when they're ready for a second set of eyes. The team can set a **List Limit** (with the List Limit Power-up) on the number of cards in Code Review, as a visual indicator for when the team needs to prioritize reviews rather than picking up new work. 

6. Once cards move through **Testing** and eventually ship to production, move them to **Done** and celebrate!

listing.description:
# Add Image - by imgX
Images are great when describing things. The same thing applies to your Trello card description as well. The problem is, to insert images in your Trello card description, you need a hosted image link. 
Well, now you can easily host your images with [imgX](https://imgx.app) and this power-up right from your card itself. This way, you can add an image to your card description in the easiest way possible. 
# Add Image - By imgX in action

![Powered By ImgX](https://imgx.app/mct2s9)
# Why choose "Add Image by imgX"?
* It's 100% Free!
* You don't need to create any accounts on imgX!
* You can add images to your card description without leaving the platform!
* It's fast, secure and easy to use!

listing.name: List Limits
listing.description:
Set a limit on your lists and we'll highlight the list if the number of cards in it passes this limit.

![Once enabled, you will find the "Set List Limit..." option in the List actions menu.](https://plugin.trello.services/images/list-limits-demo-1.gif)

![List is highlighted when you exceed the List Limit.](https://plugin.trello.services/images/list-limits-demo-2.gif)

[Check out this blog to find out how to optimize your team's process with work-in-progress limits.](https://www.atlassian.com/agile/kanban/wip-limits)

cards.desc:
A list of the things we think we want to do, maybe not quite ready for work, but high likelihood of being worked on.

This is the staging area where specs should get fleshed out.

No limit on the list size, but we should reconsider if it gets long.
cards.name: Backlog

cards.desc:
This is a list of things that are good to pull off to work on, prioritized.

If there are too few items here, we should swarm against getting tasks ready for work.
cards.name: To Do

cards.desc:
These are the things that folks are working on.

All our engineers should have at least one item in this state.

If there are too few things here, they should be pulled off Todo.

When doing is done, cards move to Code Review.
cards.name: Doing

cards.desc:
This list is for items in code review. 

When a task has gotten approval, it moves off to Testing.

If there are too many cards here, we should break off from other tasks to get code review done.
cards.name: Code Review

This list has the List Limits Power-up enabled, to help the team prioritize and remove bottlenecks before picking up new work. The list will be highlighted if the number of cards in it passes the limit that the team determines based on team size.

cards.desc:
Cards come here after being code reviewed, and we're in a place for QA and fixing things QA finds. Design review also happens at this stage.

If we have too many cards here, we should throw a flag and figure out whether we're building things that take too many passes of QA, or if we're bottlenecked on QA time.
cards.name: Testing
